The issue is that the recursive call of the `trace` function may cause a stack overflow error when the number of recursive calls is too large. To fix this error, one solution is to use an iterative approach instead of a recursive approach. Here is the fixed code using an iterative approach:

```
private void trace(int[] result, int[] edges, int low, int high, int i, int width, int height) {
    result[i] = 255;
    LinkedList<Integer> queue = new LinkedList<>();
    queue.offer(i);

    while (!queue.isEmpty()) {
        int currIndex = queue.poll();
        int currX = currIndex % width;
        int currY = currIndex / width;

        for (int j = -1; j <= 1; j++) {
            for (int k = -1; k <= 1; k++) {
                int neighborX = currX + k;
                int neighborY = currY + j;
                int neighborIndex = neighborY * width + neighborX;

                if (neighborX >= 0 && neighborX < width && 
                    neighborY >= 0 && neighborY < height &&
                    neighborIndex >= 0 && neighborIndex < edges.length &&
                    result[neighborIndex] == 0 && edges[neighborIndex] >= low &&
                    edges[neighborIndex] <= high) {
                    result[neighborIndex] = 255;
                    queue.offer(neighborIndex);
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
